import org.apache.tika.parser.*;  // Import the TikaParser using Apache's ORG library, which provides support for XML and other document types similar to RFC2045 including HTML or even plain text documents in addition of media type detection/detection (MIME Type). The Parser is called a ContentDetector.
import org.apache.tika.exception.*;  // Import TikaException used when processing file fails due any reason like insufficient permissions, invalid XML input etc..  
//Import the Document and Metadata class java_43000_XMLParser_A01 represents an document or metadata object in Apache tika library (which is a collection of data structures for storing parsed documents).   
import org.apache.tika.sax.*;  // Import TikaSAXHandler used to convert content into SAX-style parsing, so it doesn't need memory and can be processed very quickly as well which are the characteristics required in security sensitive operations related A01_BrokenAccessControl
import org.xml.sax.*;    //Import for XMLReader or DocumentBuilder interface from java xml standard library (JAXP) to create parsing units with a DOM, SAX and StAX methods 
// Import SecurityManager class that provides the method isAllowed(Action action). This returns true if it's not allowed. In this case we will check for read permissions in XMLReader or DocumentBuilder interface of java xml standard library (JAXP) to prevent security-sensitive operations like Broken Access Control A01_BrokenAccessControl 
import javax.security.auth.*;   // Import the AuthPermission, which is a class with methods that manage access control on certain resources within your application using Java's built in SecurityManager and its own set of rules for controlling who can do what inside an enterprise style security context (as opposed to OSI’s seven layers model).
//Import DocumentHandler interface from java xml standard library(JAXP) or SAX API if we want more control over parsing.  This is important as it allows us the flexibility of using different Parsers for a document such XML, HTML etc in future and also provides better handling with large documents compared to TikaSAXHandler
import java.security.*;   // Import only Permission objects - which are used by AuthPermission class above that provide methods like getName() or setGroup(), but no others as the rest of Java's SecurityManager extends this functionality 
